  "prompt": "Should my quadruplet brothers and I apply to HYS together if we aren't academically similar (test score wise)?",
  "response": "Applying to Harvard, Yale, and Stanford (HYS) as quadruplets can be a unique and compelling story for your college applications. However, whether you should apply together depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Individual Academic Qualifications**: Admissions decisions are primarily based on individual merits. If your test scores and academic achievements vary significantly, each of you should consider whether you meet the competitive standards of these schools independently. If one or more of you do not meet these standards, it might be more strategic to apply to other schools where your profiles are a better fit.\n\n2. **Personal Interests and Goals**: Each of you should prioritize schools that align with your personal interests, academic goals, and career aspirations. Applying to the same schools just because you are quadruplets might not be the best decision if those schools do not suit each individual's needs.\n\n3. **Diversity in Applications**: Applying to a range of schools can increase the chances that each of you will get into a college that is a great fit. Consider including a mix of reach, match, and safety schools in your applications.\n\n4. **Unique Story**: If you do decide to apply to HYS together, make sure to highlight your unique story as quadruplets. This can be a compelling narrative, but it should complement strong individual applications.\n\n5. **Consulting with Counselors**: Discuss your situation with your school counselors or educational consultants. They can provide personalized advice based on your specific academic profiles and help you make informed decisions.\n\nUltimately, while applying together can be a fun and unique approach, each of you should focus on finding the best fit for your individual needs and qualifications.",
